 democratic institutions and derail economic growth, The Labor of Development shows that the political and economic inclusion of industrial and agricultural workers in Kerala set the stage for a democratically negotiated capitalist transformation.When compared to the other Indian states, Kerala's departure from the national pattern is tied to its history of social movements and highlights the significance of understanding sub-national patterns of democratic consolidation and state building. The case of Kerala provides important theoretical insights into the circumstances under which the expansion of political and social citizenship can become the basis for managing economic change. Using examples from agriculture, industry, and the informal sector, Patrick Heller examines the institutional and political dynamics through which the demands of organized labor and the imperatives of capitalist growth have evolved from a period of open conflict and stagnation to one of class compromise. He also demonstrates that the Kerala model has broad ramifications for understanding the relationship between substantive democracy and market economies in low-income countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aLabor movementzIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aLabor unionszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aPeasantszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aWorking classzIndiazKeralaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aSocial Work. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172073440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501720734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501720734.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell Univer